{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3070b700-5e00-4d02-8a55-9c64e7103bf6","content":"This is a well-known MTP behavioral difference. **Exit code 8 = \"no tests discovered\"** — MTP treats this as an error, whereas VSTest silently returned 0.\n\nSince your tests are conditionally compiled (`#if INCLUDE_SLOW_TESTS`), assemblies without that define produce zero tests, triggering exit code 8.\n\n**Fix — pick one:**\n\n1. **CI command-level** (recommended): add `--ignore-exit-code 8` to your `dotnet test` invocation:\n   ```\n   dotnet test --ignore-exit-code 8\n   ```\n\n2. **Environment variable** (useful for pipeline-wide config):\n   ```\n   TESTINGPLATFORM_EXITCODE_IGNORE=8\n   ```\n\nBoth approaches only suppress the \"no tests found\" exit code — genuine test failures (exit code 2) still fail the pipeline.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bf3948d8-16ee-4665-8d3e-d42b66ce8d04","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a classic MTP migration issue. With MTP, exit code 8 means \"no tests were discovered.\" VSTest returned 0 in this case, but MTP treats it as an error by default.\n\nThere are two ways to fix this:\n\n1. **Environment variable**: Set `TESTINGPLATFORM_EXITCODE_IGNORE` to `8` (or use `--ignore-exit-code 8` CLI argument)\n2. **MSBuild property**: Set `<TestingPlatformExitCodeOnNoTests>0</TestingPlatformExitCodeOnNoTests>` in the project file — but I'm not sure if this exact property exists. \n\nActually, the most reliable approach is using the CLI flag `--ignore-exit-code 8` when running `dotnet test`, which tells the testing platform not to treat exit code 8 as a failure. The environment variable approach also works, but the fix is really meant to be handled at the CI/pipeline level rather than through MSBuild properties.","outputTokens":688,"requestId":"7C17:2A766B:135895A:15D31F3:69F94056"},"id":"b1c78269-c705-40e8-a3f7-63c06eba2a0f","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:57:11.664Z","parentId":"8a7b72d3-efef-40be-8e14-06ea726a55c1"}
